{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 11:40:56.963480", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall network health: Core, server farm, and the 10.2.1.0/24 access domain are healthy. Routing and service reachability via OSPF are working end-to-end for those segments.\\n- Identified outage: The 10.1.1.0/24 access domain is isolated. Hosts behind router_dist_1_1 do not obtain IP addresses and cannot reach any routed services (DNS, DHCP, web farm).\\n\\nFindings and Evidence\\n\\n1) Host-level reachability\\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.0/24):\\n  - DHCP OK: Has dynamic IP 10.2.1.10/24 with default route via 10.2.1.1.\\n  - End-to-end OK: Can ping dns_server (10.200.0.2) and web_server_0 (10.200.0.3). Curl to http://web99.local succeeds with normal timings (~1.07 s total).\\n  - Design-aligned behavior: Ping to backend_web_0 (20.200.0.2) returns “Destination Net Unreachable” from 10.2.1.1, which is consistent with the design that backend web servers are not directly accessible from hosts.\\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.0/24):\\n  - No IP address: No IPv4 address configured; routing table is empty; any ping results in “Network is unreachable.”\\n  - DNS cannot be used (no IP configuration); curl attempts show near-zero times indicative of immediate failure (no network).\\n\\n2) Distribution layer – router_dist_1_1 (serving 10.1.1.0/24)\\n- OSPF state:\\n  - No neighbors in OSPF (show ip ospf neighbor reports 0).\\n  - OSPF configuration uses Area 66 for both 10.1.1.0/24 and the core-facing link 172.16.0.6/31.\\n- Core-side OSPF for the same link:\\n  - router_core_1 has 172.16.0.6/31 in area 1 (not 66). This area mismatch prevents adjacency from forming.\\n  - router_core_1 does not have route to 10.1.1.0/24 (“Network not in table”).\\n- Routing table (router_dist_1_1):\\n  - Only directly connected routes (10.1.1.0/24 and 172.16.0.6/31). No routes to server farm (10.200.0.0/24) or other infrastructure.\\n- DHCP relay on router_dist_1_1:\\n  - isc-dhcp-relay service is inactive.\\n  - /etc/default/isc-dhcp-relay has empty SERVERS and INTERFACES (unconfigured).\\n  - From router_dist_1_1, ping to dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) fails: “Network is unreachable” (consistent with no OSPF adjacency).\\n- L2 indicators:\\n  - ARP on router_dist_1_1 shows an entry for 10.1.1.10 with host_1_1_1_1’s MAC, indicating L2 is up toward the host but L3/DHCP is not functioning.\\n\\n3) Distribution layer – router_dist_2_1 (serving 10.2.1.0/24)\\n- OSPF state:\\n  - Full adjacency with core (neighbors up on eth0).\\n  - OSPF routes installed, including O> 10.200.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.8.\\n- DHCP reachability:\\n  - Can ping dhcp_server (10.200.0.8) successfully with low RTT (~2–3 ms).\\n- DHCP relay service status:\\n  - isc-dhcp-relay reports inactive, yet the host has a dynamic lease. This suggests DHCP relay may be provided via a different mechanism/process not visible via this service, or the status output is not authoritative for the active relay mechanism on this node. Given successful DHCP and end-to-end connectivity, this is not currently impacting service.\\n\\n4) Core and server access routing\\n- Core routers (router_core_1/2/3) have cohesive OSPF adjacencies in backbone area 0 and inter-core links.\\n- server_access_router participates in OSPF and advertises the server farm 10.200.0.0/24. It has full adjacency to core_3; core routers have routes for server farm networks.\\n- Load balancer and web servers are reachable from the healthy access domain (10.2.1.0/24).\\n\\nAnomalies Detected\\n- Major: OSPF area mismatch on router_dist_1_1 (uses area 66) versus core (area 1) for the 172.16.0.6/31 link. This prevents OSPF adjacency and isolates 10.1.1.0/24 from the routed network.\\n- Major: DHCP relay on router_dist_1_1 is unconfigured and inactive (SERVERS and INTERFACES empty; service inactive). Even with routing fixed, DHCP would not be relayed to the central DHCP server.\\n- Resulting symptom: host_1_1_1_1 has no IP address and cannot reach DHCP, DNS, or any routed services.\\n\\nFault Localization\\n- Primary faulty device: router_dist_1_1.\\n  - Misconfigured OSPF area on core-facing interface and LAN network.\\n  - DHCP relay not configured/started on the distribution node serving 10.1.1.0/24.\\n\\nRoot Cause\\n- Misconfiguration on router_dist_1_1:\\n  - OSPF area mismatch (area 66 on router_dist_1_1 vs. area 1 on router_core_1 for 172.16.0.6/31) breaks adjacency and routing.\\n  - DHCP relay not set up (no SERVERS/INTERFACES, inactive service), so clients on 10.1.1.0/24 cannot obtain leases.\\n- Impact: Complete loss of L3 service for the 10.1.1.0/24 access domain; DHCP, DNS resolution, and access to 10.200.0.0/24 are unavailable from hosts behind switch_access_1_1_1.\\n\\nNon-Issues/Expected Behavior\\n- Direct access to backend web servers (e.g., 20.200.0.2) from hosts yields “Destination Net Unreachable” from the distribution router. This aligns with the stated design that backend servers are not directly accessible from user subnets., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='8aea59fb-79d3-4e84-85bd-07ee5fb6798b'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
